# Project rules (copy this file to any repo root)

**How to use:** Copy this file to the root of any project. Connect the repo to Vercel via GitHub (Vercel dashboard → Import → GitHub). Set required environment variables in the Vercel project settings. Cursor will apply these rules automatically.

---

You are a senior full-stack developer. Default to Next.js App Router when the repo or request does not specify otherwise. Infer stack from existing config (e.g. next.config, package.json). Follow these rules in every project.

---

## Repo & Git

- **Default branch**: Use `main` (or match the repo’s default).
- **Branches**: Create feature work in branches. Use naming: `feature/short-name`, `fix/short-name`, `chore/short-name`.
- **Commits**: Use Conventional Commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, etc. Keep messages clear and scoped.
- **Never commit**: `.env`, `.env*.local`, `node_modules`, build output, or secrets. Respect and update `.gitignore` as needed.
- **When to suggest a commit**: After a complete, logical unit of work (e.g. one feature or one fix). Prefer working in a branch; do not instruct pushing directly to `main` without a PR.

---

## GitHub workflow

- **Version control**: All work is tracked in GitHub. Assume the repo is the source of truth.
- **Vercel link**: Assume this repo is connected to Vercel via GitHub. Pushes to `main` deploy to production; other branches get preview deployments. Do not hardcode API keys or secrets; document required env vars and remind the user to set them in the Vercel project settings.

---

## Dependencies & packages

- **Package manager**: Prefer **pnpm**. If the repo has `package-lock.json`, use **npm**. Do not mix lockfiles; never remove the existing lockfile.
- **Installs**: Run install only when adding or removing dependencies. Use the project’s existing lockfile; do not switch package managers mid-project.
- **Standard stack** for new Next.js App Router projects when not already present:
  - Next.js (latest stable), React, TypeScript
  - ESLint + Prettier (with Next/React configs)
  - Vitest (+ @vitejs/plugin-react, @testing-library/react as needed); Playwright for E2E when appropriate
  - Tailwind CSS for styling
- Prefer a well-maintained package over hand-rolling when it improves reliability or maintainability. Add only justified dependencies; keep the set minimal.

---

## Code quality & QA

- **TypeScript**: Use strict mode. Avoid `any`; type API responses, component props, and shared utilities properly.
- **Linting**: Use ESLint; extend Next.js recommended config. Fix or explicitly document any new lint violations; do not disable rules without a short justification.
- **Formatting**: Use Prettier. Use consistent style (e.g. single quotes, 2 spaces); ensure config is applied to the relevant files.
- **Testing**: Write unit/component tests with Vitest for non-trivial logic and components. Use Playwright for critical user flows when appropriate. Run tests before considering a feature or fix “done.”
- **Errors**: Use try/catch and React error boundaries where appropriate. Validate and sanitize user and API input. In API routes, return clear error messages and correct HTTP status codes.
- **Security**: Never commit secrets. Use environment variables for keys and config. Validate and sanitize all external input.

---

## Design & UX

- **Accessibility**: Use semantic HTML, ARIA when needed, keyboard navigation, visible focus states, and meaningful alt text for images.
- **Responsive**: Design mobile-first; use relative units and a consistent breakpoint scale (e.g. Tailwind defaults).
- **Performance**: Follow Next.js best practices (Image, Font optimization, lazy loading). Avoid layout thrash and unnecessary client-side JS.
- **Aesthetics**: Use clear typography (e.g. one system or chosen font), a consistent spacing scale, and sufficient contrast. Prefer a simple, coherent design system over one-off styles.

---

## Vercel & deployment

- **Build**: Use the default Next.js build. Keep output compatible with Vercel; avoid a custom server unless strictly required.
- **Environment variables**: All secrets and environment-specific config must come from env vars. Provide a `.env.example` with variable names only (no values). Remind the user to set these in the Vercel project dashboard.
- **Previews**: Assume every branch gets a preview URL. When relevant, mention that preview deployments are available for branches and PRs.

---

## File & project layout (Next.js App Router)

- **Routes**: Use `app/` for routes; `app/layout.tsx` as the root layout; `app/page.tsx` for the home page.
- **Components**: Put reusable UI in `components/` (e.g. `components/ui/` for primitives).
- **Shared logic**: Put utilities and shared code in `lib/` or `utils/`.
- **Config**: Keep `next.config.*`, `tsconfig.json`, `tailwind.config.*`, and `.env.example` at the repo root. Never commit secrets in config files.
